c forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Garlande","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gerlond</i>, <i>ger(e)land</i>, <i>garlond</i> ‘metal chaplet, crown, coronet; wreath’, probably a nickname denoting a habitual wearer of such items, or a metonymic occupational name for a maker of them.","English: perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Gerland</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Garuland</i>, probably from <i>garw-</i> ‘war-gear; prepared(ness)’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’; the first element of the French name may instead be from a name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde de Garlande was born about 1150, in Gournay, Seine-et-Oise, France. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mattheus Van Montmorency Heer Van Marly III. She died on 16 March 1224, in France, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1150–16 mars 1224":"umbes 1150–16. märts 1224","1135–1204":"1135–1204","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1170–1226":"1170–1226","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1150–1224":"1150–1224","about 1150":"umbes 1150","environ 1200":"umbes 1200","1175":"1175","16 mars 1224":"16. märts 1224","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1204":"1204","1226":"1226","122